  "prompt": "What is the stall speed and AOA of an f-14 with wings fully swept back?",
  "response": "The stall speed and angle of attack (AOA) of an F-14 Tomcat with its wings fully swept back depend on several factors, including altitude, load, and configuration (e.g., fuel load, payload, and engine thrust). However, some general estimates can be provided based on historical data and aerodynamic principles.\n\n### Stall Speed:\nWith its wings fully swept back (68\u00b0 sweep), the F-14's stall speed increases due to the reduced lift-producing area of the wings. At a typical combat weight and sea level, the stall speed of the F-14 in this configuration is estimated to be in the range of **160-180 knots (185-207 mph or 296-333 km/h)**. This value would increase at higher altitudes or with heavier loads.\n\n### Angle of Attack (AOA):\nThe critical angle of attack (the AOA at which the wing stalls) for the F-14 with wings swept back is typically around **15-20 degrees**. This is the point at which the airflow over the wings separates, causing a loss of lift.\n\n### Notes:\n- The F-14's variable-sweep wing design allows it to optimize performance for different flight regimes, but the fully swept configuration sacrifices some lift for reduced drag at high speeds.\n- The F-14's flight control system and leading-edge slats help manage stall characteristics, but fully sweeping the wings reduces their effectiveness.\n\nExact numbers can vary depending on specific conditions, but these ranges provide a reasonable estimate for the F-14 in its fully swept configuration.",
